INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ca835987-ba49-4407-9916-dc22198bc40e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Code Splitting — Manual Chunks, Dynamic Imports, and Route-Based Splitting$escape$,
  $escape$webpack splits code through three complementary mechanisms. Dynamic imports (`import()`) are the foundation — webpack treats every `import()` call as a split point and emits a separate chunk. For route-based splitting, wrap each route component in a dynamic import; webpack resolves the dependency graph at build time and defers loading until the route activates.

Manual chunks via `optimization.splitChunks` give you surgical control. The `cacheGroups` API lets you extract vendor libraries, shared utilities, or any module subset into named chunks. Setting `chunks: 'all'` enables splitting across both async and initial chunks — critical for extracting large deps like `lodash` or `react-dom` that would otherwise bloat your entry bundle.

Magic comments let you name async chunks and control loading behavior: `/* webpackChunkName: 'dashboard' */` sets the output filename, while `/* webpackPrefetch: true */` instructs the browser to prefetch the chunk during idle time using a `<link rel='prefetch'>` tag injected by webpack's runtime.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js
module.exports = {
  optimization: {
    splitChunks: {
      chunks: 'all',
      cacheGroups: {
        vendor: {
          test: /[\\/]node_modules[\\/]/,
          name: 'vendors',
          priority: 10,
        },
        shared: {
          minChunks: 2,
          name: 'shared',
          reuseExistingChunk: true,
        },
      },
    },
  },
};

// Route-level dynamic import with chunk naming + prefetch
const Dashboard = React.lazy(
  () => import(/* webpackChunkName: 'dashboard' */ /* webpackPrefetch: true */ './Dashboard')
);$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
