INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0082582a-8b56-44e3-b452-07e8507eff6c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Tree Shaking — How It Works and Why sideEffects Matters$escape$,
  $escape$webpack's tree shaking relies on ES module static analysis. Because `import`/`export` bindings are resolved at parse time — not runtime — webpack can build a precise dependency graph and mark unused exports as dead code for Terser to eliminate.

The critical lever is the `sideEffects` field in `package.json`. Without it, webpack assumes every module has side effects (think polyfills that mutate globals) and won't drop unused files. Set `"sideEffects": false` to tell webpack the entire package is pure. For packages with some side-effectful files, use an array: `"sideEffects": ["*.css", "./src/polyfill.js"]`.

Your own source needs the same treatment. In `webpack.config.js`, set `optimization.sideEffects: true` (default in production mode) to respect `package.json` hints. Combine with `optimization.usedExports: true` so webpack annotates unused exports with `/* unused harmony export */` before Terser strips them.

Common pitfall: CommonJS (`require()`) breaks tree shaking entirely — webpack can't statically analyze dynamic requires. Ensure your libraries ship ESM via the `module` field in `package.json`.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js
module.exports = {
  mode: 'production',
  optimization: {
    usedExports: true,   // marks unused exports for Terser
    sideEffects: true,   // respects package.json "sideEffects" field
  },
};

// package.json (your library or app)
{
  "sideEffects": ["*.css"],  // CSS has side effects; JS modules are pure
  "module": "dist/index.esm.js"  // ESM entry for tree shaking
}$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
