INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8274e169-99e3-44a1-82bb-5a90055d2d30',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Source Maps — Picking the Right devtool for Production$escape$,
  $escape$webpack's `devtool` option controls source map generation, and the wrong choice in production either tanks performance or leaks your source code. There are 20+ variants, but production decisions usually come down to three.

`source-map` generates a separate `.map` file linked via `//# sourceMappingURL`. Full fidelity, safest for production — restrict access at the CDN/server level so end users can't fetch the map. Build time is slowest.

`hidden-source-map` generates the same file but omits the `sourceMappingURL` comment. Perfect for error monitoring tools like Sentry that upload maps directly via their webpack plugin — users never see the link, but your error tracker can symbolicate stack traces.

`nosources-source-map` includes line/column mappings but strips original source content from the map file. Safe to expose publicly — gives you usable stack traces in DevTools without exposing proprietary code.

Avoid `eval-*` variants in production entirely — they use `eval()`, break CSP, and inflate bundle size. Set `devtool` per environment using webpack's `--env` flag or separate config files, never hardcode a single value.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js
const { merge } = require('webpack-merge');
const base = require('./webpack.base.js');

module.exports = (env) =>
  merge(base, {
    mode: 'production',
    devtool: env.sentryUpload
      ? 'hidden-source-map'   // Sentry plugin uploads, URL hidden from browser
      : 'nosources-source-map', // Safe to expose; no source content leaked
    plugins: [
      env.sentryUpload && new SentryWebpackPlugin({
        include: './dist',
        ignore: ['node_modules'],
      }),
    ].filter(Boolean),
  });$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
