INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'dab86e08-0b2c-4c98-99db-f187c13b4779',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Path Aliases — Clean Imports with resolve.alias$escape$,
  $escape$Deeply nested relative imports like `../../../components/Button` are fragile and hard to refactor. webpack's `resolve.alias` lets you map shorthand tokens to absolute paths, eliminating traversal chains entirely.

In `webpack.config.js`, set `resolve.alias` to an object where each key is the alias token and the value is an absolute path — typically built with `path.resolve(__dirname, 'src/...')`. webpack rewrites matching import prefixes at bundle time, so `@components/Button` resolves directly to `src/components/Button`.

For TypeScript projects, mirror every alias in `tsconfig.json` under `compilerOptions.paths` — webpack and `tsc` resolve modules independently, so both configs must stay in sync. Use `tsconfig-paths-webpack-plugin` if you'd rather maintain a single source of truth in `tsconfig.json` and have webpack read paths from there automatically.

Aliases also work with `resolve.modules` for global lookup directories, but `resolve.alias` is more explicit and predictable. Prefer exact aliases over directory-level module roots to avoid ambiguous resolutions across loaders.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js
const path = require('path');

module.exports = {
  resolve: {
    alias: {
      '@components': path.resolve(__dirname, 'src/components'),
      '@utils': path.resolve(__dirname, 'src/utils'),
      '@hooks': path.resolve(__dirname, 'src/hooks'),
    },
    extensions: ['.ts', '.tsx', '.js'],
  },
};$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
