INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ff2080c8-41ee-4ad5-85c8-80d6aae2cc22',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack vs Vite's Dev Pipeline: Native ESM, esbuild Pre-Bundling, and Rollup Explained for webpack Users$escape$,
  $escape$webpack bundles the entire module graph before the browser sees a single byte — even in dev. Every `import` is resolved, transformed, and stitched into a bundle upfront via its JavaScript-based compiler. Vite inverts this: in dev mode it serves raw ES modules directly over HTTP, letting the browser do import resolution on demand. `node_modules` are pre-bundled once by esbuild (written in Go, 10–100× faster than webpack's JS pipeline), then cached. Only request-triggered modules are processed per save.

In production, Vite swaps esbuild for Rollup because Rollup's tree-shaking and code-splitting output is more mature. webpack's production mode achieves comparable results via `optimization.usedExports: true`, `optimization.sideEffects: true`, and `TerserPlugin`.

The critical caveat for webpack users evaluating Vite: Vite's dev and prod pipelines run on two different bundlers. Module resolution edge cases that pass in dev can silently fail in production. webpack's unified pipeline — one bundler, one config, both modes — eliminates this class of parity bug. webpack 5's `experiments.lazyCompilation` narrows the cold-start gap without sacrificing that consistency.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js — approximating Vite's on-demand dev serving
module.exports = {
  mode: 'development',
  experiments: {
    lazyCompilation: {
      entries: true,   // compile entry points only on first request
      imports: true,   // compile dynamic imports only when hit
    },
  },
  optimization: {
    runtimeChunk: 'single',
    splitChunks: {
      cacheGroups: {
        vendor: {
          test: /[\\/]node_modules[\\/]/,
          name: 'vendors',
          chunks: 'all', // analogous to esbuild pre-bundle cache
        },
      },
    },
  },
};$escape$,
