INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '4dc25f38-c5ad-4e45-b2a0-412d02b0a6cc',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Loaders vs Plugins — And Where Module Federation Fits$escape$,
  $escape$Loaders and plugins operate at different pipeline stages. Loaders transform individual module files before they enter the dependency graph — `babel-loader` transpiles JS, `css-loader` resolves `@import`, `raw-loader` inlines assets as strings. They run per-file, chained right-to-left in the `use` array. Plugins hook into webpack's compiler lifecycle via Tapable events (`emit`, `compilation`, `afterOptimize`) and operate on the entire bundle graph — `MiniCssExtractPlugin` pulls CSS out of JS chunks, `BundleAnalyzerPlugin` instruments the `done` hook.

Module Federation sits at the plugin level but redefines the module resolution contract entirely. `ModuleFederationPlugin` exposes and consumes remote chunks at runtime, not build time. The host app's webpack runtime fetches remote entry manifests, resolves shared singletons (e.g. a single React instance across microfrontends), and loads federated modules via async dynamic `import()`. Critically, shared dependencies declared in `shared: { react: { singleton: true } }` are deduplicated across remotes — without this, each remote bundles its own React, breaking hook state.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js — host app consuming a remote
const { ModuleFederationPlugin } = require('webpack').container;

module.exports = {
  plugins: [
    new ModuleFederationPlugin({
      name: 'host',
      remotes: {
        checkout: 'checkout@https://cdn.example.com/checkout/remoteEntry.js',
      },
      shared: {
        react: { singleton: true, requiredVersion: '^19.0.0' },
        'react-dom': { singleton: true, requiredVersion: '^19.0.0' },
      },
    }),
  ],
};$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
