INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9b5da339-1890-4418-a59c-b2e9a36e725a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Build Monitoring — Track Build Times and Catch Bundle Regressions in CI$escape$,
  $escape$webpack's `StatsPlugin` and the built-in `stats` object give you precise per-asset, per-chunk timing data. Pipe `stats.toJson({ timings: true, assets: true })` to a JSON file after every build, then diff it in CI to catch regressions before they merge.

For build time tracking, wrap `webpack()` in a Node script and read `stats.endTime - stats.startTime`. For bundle size gates, use `webpack-bundle-analyzer`'s `statsFilename` output or the lighter `bundlesize` package, which reads your `stats.json` and enforces per-asset byte limits defined in `package.json`.

In GitHub Actions, store the `stats.json` as a build artifact and compare it against the baseline from `main` using a custom script or the `relative-ci/agent` action, which posts a PR comment with a size diff table. Set `performance.hints: 'error'` in your webpack config to fail the build outright when any asset breaches `performance.maxAssetSize` or `performance.maxEntrypointSize` thresholds — no external tooling required for hard limits.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js
module.exports = {
  performance: {
    hints: process.env.CI ? 'error' : 'warning',
    maxAssetSize: 250_000,        // 250 kB per asset
    maxEntrypointSize: 400_000,   // 400 kB per entrypoint
  },
  plugins: [
    new (require('webpack-bundle-analyzer').BundleAnalyzerPlugin)({
      analyzerMode: 'disabled',
      generateStatsFile: true,
      statsFilename: 'bundle-stats.json',
    }),
  ],
};$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
